Powered by RubiQube Ad Network Egypt”s Foreign Minister Sameh Shoukry has reiterated his country”s willingness to foster political cooperation with Senegal during a meeting with his Senegalese peer Amado Ba, the Foreign Ministry reported in Cairo on Thursday. The source said that the meeting was held on the margins of the preparatory meetings for the 14th Summit Conference of the Islamic Cooperation Organization (OIC) to be held on May 31 in Mecca, Saudi Arabia. According to Egyptian Foreign Ministry spokesman Ahmed Hafez, Shoukry praised the role played by Senegalese President Macky Sall, leading the New Alliance for Africa Development. The diplomat also highlighted the historical and fraternal ties with Senegal, especially at the political, cultural and religious levels. Shoukry also highlighted the importance of continuous coordination between the two countries within the framework of the Organization of Islamic Cooperation, given that Senegal is one of the major Islamic countries in Africa. The FM affirmed his country’s intention to strengthen bilateral relations, underlining the key role Egypt has played as the current President of the African Union.